<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is an antipode?", answer: "An antipode is the point on the surface of the Earth that is diametrically opposite to a given location. If you drew a line through your current position all the way through the center of the Earth and out the other side, the point where it exits the surface is your antipode. Mathematically, to find the antipode you negate the latitude and add 180 degrees to the longitude (wrapping the result into the -180 to 180 range)." },
  { question: "If I dig straight down, where do I end up?", answer: "For the vast majority of Earth's land area, the antipode is somewhere in the ocean, not another continent. About 15 percent of land has an antipode that is also land, and most of the remaining land points to open sea. Popular land-to-land antipodes include parts of Argentina to China, New Zealand to Spain, Hawaii to Botswana, and Malaysia to Ecuador. The iconic image of digging from the United States to China is a myth: a hole drilled straight down from the continental US would emerge in the Indian Ocean." },
  { question: "Why are most antipodes in ocean?", answer: "Oceans cover about 71 percent of Earth's surface, so by area any random antipode has a 71 percent chance of landing in water. In addition, most of Earth's land is concentrated in the Northern Hemisphere, while most of the opposite hemispheres are ocean. The distribution of continents makes land-on-land antipodes relatively rare. A famous exception is Madrid, whose antipode sits near Weber, New Zealand, close enough that the two towns are considered twin antipodes." },
  { question: "How is antipode related to travel?", answer: "A flight to your antipode is the longest possible flight on Earth, because any path between two antipodal points covers half of the planet's circumference, about 20,000 kilometers. Because great-circle paths between antipodes are infinite (every great circle passes through both antipodal points), there is no unique shortest route, and all directions are equally correct headings at the start. In practice, airlines pick routes that hug favorable winds and avoid restricted airspace." },
  { question: "Can I use this for jet lag or astronomy?", answer: "Yes. Your antipode is always on the opposite day-night cycle and in a time zone roughly 12 hours offset from yours. At solar noon where you are, it is solar midnight at your antipode. Astronomers use antipodal points to identify opposite zeniths and to plan observation campaigns that share the same star chart but twelve hours apart." }
]) %>

